take inhibitors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits monoamine oxidase enzyme","Antagonises postsynaptic serotonin receptors","Stimulates presynaptic serotonin release","Blocks noradrenaline transporter protein","Blocks serotonin transporter protein"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESelective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) such as sertraline and fluoxetine work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking serotonin transporter protein\u003C/strong\u003E on presynaptic neurons. This leads to increased serotonin concentration in the synaptic cleft and enhanced serotonergic neurotransmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting monoamine oxidase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E represents the mechanism of monoamine oxidase inhibitors (e.g. phenelzine), which prevent the breakdown of several neurotransmitters including serotonin, noradrenaline and dopamine. \u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonising postsynaptic serotonin receptors\u003C/strong\u003E would decrease rather than enhance serotonergic neurotransmission. SSRIs do not directly affect serotonin release from presynaptic terminals, so \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulating presynaptic serotonin release\u003C/strong\u003E does not describe their action. \u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking noradrenaline transporter protein\u003C/strong\u003E represents the mechanism of noradrenaline reuptake inhibitors (e.g. reboxetine) and partially of tricyclic antidepressants (e.g. amitriptyline).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe therapeutic effects of SSRIs are due to increased serotonergic neurotransmission in the synaptic cleft.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors work by blocking the serotonin transporter protein in presynaptic neurons, increasing serotonin in the synaptic cleft.","Tricyclic antidepressants block both serotonin and noradrenaline reuptake transporters.","Monoamine oxidase inhibitors prevent the enzymatic breakdown of serotonin, noradrenaline, and dopamine."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook (online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from: https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al. Rang and Dale\u0027s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96061"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14682"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96061"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T22:45:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T22:45:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7375"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114046"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data"